editorial:
**State**: `dp[i][j]` = number of distinct ways to pick `t[0..j-1]` as a subsequence from `s[0..i-1]`.

**Recurrence**:
- If `s[i-1] === t[j-1]`: we can either match this char (`dp[i-1][j-1]`) or skip it (`dp[i-1][j]`). Sum them.
- Else: must skip `s[i-1]`: `dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j]`.

**Base**: `dp[i][0] = 1` (empty `t` matches in exactly one way — pick nothing). `dp[0][j] = 0` for `j > 0`.

```javascript
function distinctSubsequences(s, t) {
  const m = s.length, n = t.length;
  if (n > m) return 0;
  const dp = new Array(n + 1).fill(0);
  dp[0] = 1;
  for (let i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
    for (let j = n; j >= 1; j--) {
      if (s[i-1] === t[j-1]) dp[j] = dp[j] + dp[j-1];
    }
  }
  return dp[n];
}
```

**Time**: O(m*n). **Space**: O(n) — iterate `j` right-to-left so `dp[j-1]` still holds the previous row's value.

