**State**: `dp[i][j]` = does `p[0..j-1]` match `s[0..i-1]` fully.

**Recurrence**:
- If `p[j-1]` is a normal char or `.`: `dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] && (p[j-1] === '.' || p[j-1] === s[i-1])`.
- If `p[j-1]` is `*`:
  - Zero of the preceding token: `dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-2]`.
  - One or more, if the preceding token matches `s[i-1]`: also OR with `dp[i-1][j]`.

**Base**: `dp[0][0] = true`. For `j >= 2`, if `p[j-1]` is `*`, `dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2]` (the `x*` group can match empty).

```javascript
function regexMatch(s, p) {
  const m = s.length, n = p.length;
  const dp = Array.from({length: m + 1}, () => new Array(n + 1).fill(false));
  dp[0][0] = true;
  for (let j = 2; j <= n; j++) if (p[j-1] === '*') dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2];
  for (let i = 1; i <= m; i++) {
    for (let j = 1; j <= n; j++) {
      if (p[j-1] === '*') {
        dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-2] || ((p[j-2] === '.' || p[j-2] === s[i-1]) && dp[i-1][j]);
      } else {
        dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] && (p[j-1] === '.' || p[j-1] === s[i-1]);
      }
    }
  }
  return dp[m][n];
}
```

